<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8" />
  <title>Profiles Directory</title>
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />
</head>
<body>
<header>
  <h1>Profiles Directory</h1>
  <p>
    Endpoint: <code>{{ profiles_directory_url }}</code>
  </p>
</header>

<main>
  <section>
    <h2>Summary</h2>
    <p>{{ description }}</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>What Is a Profile?</h2>
    <p>
      When you call an API endpoint such as <code>/api/greeting</code>,
      the response includes data fields and navigation links. A
      <em>profile</em> is a separate document that describes that
      response: what fields it contains, what each link means, and how
      a client should interpret the data. Think of a profile as the
      instruction manual for a particular API response.
    </p>
    <p>
      Every profile is available in two formats from the same URL,
      selected by the <code>Accept</code> header you send:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>HTML</strong> (<code>Accept: text/html</code>) &mdash;
        a human-readable page that explains the endpoint's behavior,
        response fields, links, and error conditions. This is what you
        see when you open the URL in a browser, and it is useful when
        you are learning the API or writing a client for the first
        time.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>JSON Schema</strong>
        (<code>Accept: application/schema+json</code>) &mdash; a
        machine-readable document that formally describes the response
        structure. You can feed this to a JSON Schema validator library
        to automatically check that a response has the expected shape.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Profiles are organized into <em>families</em>. A family groups
      all the profiles that belong to the same API or service. Within
      a family, profiles may be versioned so that the API can evolve
      without breaking existing clients. This directory lists the
      profile families available on this server.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Directory Contents</h2>
    <p>The following profile families are available:</p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Family</th>
          <th>URL</th>
          <th>Description</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>CBRWS</td>
          <td>
            <a href="{{ cbrws_directory_url }}"><code>{{ cbrws_directory_url }}</code></a>
          </td>
          <td>
            Profiles for the CBRWS (Class Based Routing Web Service)
            API. This family contains versioned profiles that describe
            the API discovery document, resource endpoints, and custom
            link relations. Follow this link to see the available
            versions.
          </td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Content Negotiation</h2>
    <p>
      This directory is available in two formats. The format you
      receive depends on the <code>Accept</code> header in your
      request:
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th><code>Accept</code> Header</th>
          <th>What You Get</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>
            <code>application/hal+json</code> (or omitted)
          </td>
          <td>
            A HAL+JSON document listing the profile families as
            navigable links. This is the default and is intended for
            programmatic consumption.
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>text/html</code> (or a browser)</td>
          <td>This human-readable page.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>Examples using curl:</p>
    <pre><code># Fetch the machine-readable HAL+JSON directory
curl -s -H "Accept: application/hal+json" {{ profiles_directory_url }}

# Fetch the human-readable HTML page
curl -s -H "Accept: text/html" {{ profiles_directory_url }}</code></pre>
  </section>
</main>

